>>15553192

How long has it been OP?

Happened to me.

First week I couldn't taste or smell a thing. Food lost all appeal. I found myself enjoying textures. So noodles, crisps, fries (crunchy on the outside soft in the middle). Ate out of necessity.

After about 10 days, I started to get hints of sense. So started to really enjoy really salty, sweet and spicy food. I couldn't taste per se, but I could tell their was flavour there.

After about 2-3 weeks, taste returned.

I honestly think eating really strong flavoured food (salty, spicy and sweet), trying to smell everything and remember what it tasted like as I ate, slowly brought my taste back.

After 4 weeks, life is back to normal thank god.

Also protip don't smoke or drink beer - it tastes like shit.

com:
Another entry in my tea journal. I'm somewhat surprised I liked this considering its qualities, but I think the balance of them worked well. Here is my journal for the 2020 Autumn Qianjiazhai gu hua sheng pu'er from Verdant Tea:

Dry leaf smells of smoked sugar, somewhat green. Maybe faintly woodsy. Might be imagining it, but there is almost a hint of liquorice. Aromas aren't extremely potent, but noticeable and not unpleasant.


Stewed carrot smell, some pleasantly sour herbaceous funk scent. For first infusion, flavor is muted and light. May need to brew longer.

Interesting second infusion. The bitterness and sourness both settled down instead of increased. Low astringency, low to medium thickness. There is a slight herb retronasal flavor present that works well with the low bitterness. If I whip up air in my mouth after swallowing, it almost reminds me of matcha, but with less potential of sweetness.

Not getting too much forward flavor, but the body sensation is nice. It is modest and not at all intense, nor flat. Medium yellow color. I wouldn't say this is an excellent tea, but I find the subtle herb/bitter profile to be rather relaxing and gentle. I like the herb flavor/scent profile shift over time compared to the initial stewed vegetal impression. Feels somewhat nice after drinking a few infusions.

I think this is a tea that lends itself to slightly lower temperatures to round out the bitterness and bring out the herbaceousness. Water quality may also be more apparent with this leaf than with some others.

This isn't a poor tea in my opinion, though anyone looking for sweet or floral notes might be disappointed. If you like herb and mild bitter notes, and desire something understated and gentle, it's not too bad of a choice. This is a tea for when you feel dreadful, but don't want any sweet or excessively indulgent flavors blasted at you.

I keep brewing notes on hand for comfortable reference, and count down brews in my head (timers add stress and complexity to the setup). I type my notes shorthand on my phone, adding more detail in-between notes. Turkish tea is brewed with about eight tablespoons of leaves per cup of liquid, and then diluted to taste by the drinker. It's fun, but also most people do it wrong for internet pictures or maybe they just don't realize it's wrong. You should use a standard wide glass cup and press down on the bread with the rim to make the cutouts, so the remaining bread is really just a rim with squared ends to contain the egg symmetrically and make it easier to flip. Meanwhile you toast the center piece which is over half the surface area of the original slice of bread, then butter it lightly and use it to dip in the yolk. Excess yolk can be spread over the border bread.
Conversely, half cook the yolk so just the center of it is wet and spread the wet part and mushy sides over the border, and put peanut butter and jelly on the center toast instead.

Futurists have looked at this concept. Buildings with a gazillion floors aren't all that viable, and it's not because of the foundations or the materials you build it from. It's the elevators.
Suppose you live on floor 1082, but your job is on floor 802. Think of all the people that have to travel between those floors, all day, every day, and the time it takes an elevator to traverse that distance, making periodic stops at intervening floors. Other big problem, heat waste. Getting rid of excess heat (beyond what you could use for survival or power generation) is one of the biggest chokepoints for building megastructures like that. Y'all should look into some Isaac Arthur occasionally.

Overall, they produce heat. If you put a fridge in a room and let its door open, temperature in the room will increase.

AC works in a similar way, that's why there's always a unit outside to get rid of the heat and let it actually cool down the inside of your habitat.

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15561864
trick is to hold them as high up as you can.
mistake most people make is holding chopsticks too far down.
also the bottom stick doesnt move, only the top one.
lastly, it depends on the type of chopsticks too. Korea, China and Japan all make completely different shaped chopsticks because of the different food they eat.

Chinese chopsticks are fat, wooden and blunt because they're unrefined and generally dont eat finicky fiddly stuff like fish that requires dexterity to use.
Koreans use slippery metallic chopsticks with a fine tip because they used to be paranoid about poisoning each other, so using silver chopsticks helped detect poison. ALso their food is just pork, cabbage, hot sauce and cheese and they use a spoon half of the time so they dont need anything too fancy.
Japanese eat more fish than other parts of asia, so they use dexterous fine-tipped chopsticks to do things like remove bones from fish and the like.

If in doubt, go with Japanese ones.

This is really good for $35 ish bucks. It is authentic pot still distilled rum, so it has some of that funky high ester palate of bananas and other tropical fruits going on.

Ron Zacapa 23 is pretty good for $40 ish but contains a lot of added sugar. It's pretty decadent and almost like spiced rum only it really is rum and has some pretty old spirit in there.

If you throw some peanuts in a food processor, jar it up, and let it sit for a while then the oil should separate from the solids. You're basically making peanut butter, but for the oil. Oil separating is a sort of common complaint with homemade peanut butter, but it's what you want in this case. It would probably be faster and yield more oil if you put it in a cheesecloth or something and press it.

Sorry, this is incorrect.

Service √† la fran√ßaise included courses. The difference is that with Service √† la fran√ßaise, all dishes in each course would be set in a pre-determined pattern on the table at the same time. The hosts and guests would then serve each other based on what was nearby--this included not only portioning out food but carving up the meats, with staff on hand in case you wanted something that was at the opposite end of the table. Whole meats would typically be set at the head of the table as the host would be prepared to carve them.

With Service √† la russe, the meal was broken up into far more courses/services--so instead of all the dishes which would have, under the French style, been part of a single course set on the table, only each specific dish would be served at once. This is why you started seeing meals with many many courses, because rather than the first course being all savory dishes (soup, vegetables, fish); it would be soup only, then second course was vegetables, then third course was fish, etc. The only dishes set on the table would be additions that people could choose to add more of to their food, such as a sauce; dessert was sometimes used as the centerpiece, along with flowers and decorations. People were served by staff, and did not serve themselves.

Image is an example of a second course for a French service.

French royals had a tradition called dining 'en grand couvert,' which was basically eating your meal in a public ceremony. a former lady in waiting wrote:

>One of the customs most disagreeable to the Queen was that of dining every day in public. Maria Leczinska had always submitted to this wearisome practice; Marie Antoinette followed it as long as she was Dauphiness. The Dauphin dined with her, and each branch of the family had its public dinner daily. The ushers suffered all decently dressed people to enter; the sight was the delight of persons from the country. At the dinner-hour there were none to be met upon the stairs but honest folks, who, after having seen the Dauphiness take her soup, went to see the Princes eat their ‚Äòbouilli‚Äô, and then ran themselves out of breath to behold Mesdames at their dessert.

I mean, not really, in the sense that it served an entirely different purpose than a mukbang. Mukbangs are/were (depending on what you watch, I guess) about satisfying the urge to eat with someone else and fill loneliness. Grand couverts and similar rituals were

With French Royalty, the idea of the grand couvert was to elevate the social status of the French royals to the level that being allowed the privilege of watching them eat was seen as a honor.

It was a way of pacifying the nobles (since the Versailles etiquette system itself was designed to quell noble rebellion) and of making the royals into otherworldly beings to the general population.

To the nobles who were allowed to kneel or sit on stools during the grand couvert, or who were allowed to serve the royal family, or who were simply allowed the privilege of the front rows, it was a way for the royals to bestow elevated status upon them; if you were a noble, you would view the public exhibition of this privilege as a reward (I'm allowed to use a stool in front of the king! My god, how awesome I am! everyone see how much social status I have!)

To the common people who were allowed entry, it was a push and pull relationship: you are being made to think that the French monarchs "belong" to the public to the point that what you might view as an everyday meal is something they must do in front of the whole world, while also acknowledging that they are so lofty that the mere act of watching them eat is a ceremonial ritual, because they were placed there by God to rule over you common people

The idea that people were routinely stuffing in massive quantities of food in the late Victorian and then Edwardian era is a myth rooted in a misunderstanding of the courses.

You were not expected to eat every course. The idea behind the numerous courses was so that there would be something for everyone, and not everyone was expected to eat every dish. It was a way to showcase your wealth and ability to offer a wide variety of foods, rather than expecting guests to eat all that was provided to them. And you would not be given a massive portion of every course or dish.

Another interesting tidbid about the grand couvert: you would assume that the public would hate the grand couvert because it would have been a prominent example of the excess food available to a small portion of the population, while a few miles away people might be starving or hungry in Paris. Nope. The complaints about the grand couvert were that the royalty, particularly once Louis XVI became king, didn't do it enough. Marie Antoinette notoriously hated the grand couvert and convinced Louis XVI to let her only do it once a week; this pissed off people who were used to being able to see the royal family at these mealtimes, a "privilege" they were now being denied. Marie Antoinette wanting to dine in private more often than not was seen as "Austrian."

>>15563263
No.

Much like washing chicken, washing rice is a holdover behavior from the past.

Rice, as most other grains and even flours, used to be distributed in large burlap sacks to bodegas or small grocery stores. During transit, all of these products, would gather dust particles, insects and other things, so washing was necessary for rice, while sifting was mandatory for flours because you could find small stones in it (and no one wants to lose a tooth while eating bread).

Today's factory standards, make washing rice unnecessary. Sifting things like cornstarch, cake flour and cocoa powder remains because they tend to clump.

But facts aren't usually enough to dissuade people away from their learned behavior, so many continue to do all of the above.

com: Much of the price difference is in things the layman doesnt see at first glance - the quality of the steel, the heat treat and its consistency, the quality control, the geometry (cross section) of the blade, a fine balance point for a professional style pinch grip, an edge profile that is well suited for the kinds of jpb you want the knife for (more or less belly, lower or taller blade, longer or shorter flat spot etc etc)

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15559187
The main functional difference is going to be the type of steel used. Different alloys or whatever will hold sharpness differently, dictating how quickly it goes dull and you need to sharpen it or get it sharpened again. There's also ergonomic concerns like how it feels in your hand, how much weight you want, the functionality of the shape of the blade for what you're cutting, etc. Also whether the knife is full tang, partial tang, whatever. Then for the really fancy shit you're also paying for ornate decorative shit and the brand name etc

>>15558139
Honestly, it's something that plagues me, I'm constantly pondering it but never can come up with a definitive answer....truth is, I'm a bit of a fan of them all. I can tell you my favorite burgers from each I've had regularly though.

From McDonalds, I have always enjoyed their Double Cheeseburger, yes the Double Cheese, not the McDouble, I am old enough to remember when the controversial switch happened and I do think the second slice of McCheese makes for a better burger. Two Double Cheeseburgers is my go to choice.

At Burger King, I enjoy the Whopper and Whopper Jr., I find the no cheese but smokey flavored patty works very well with the salad combination and whatever brand of ketchup and mayo they use, it all works together to create a satisfying "Whopper juice" as it were, that is best sopped up with some fries off the plate.

For Wendy's, the Jr. Bacon Cheeseburger has been my classic go to. Bacon lettuce and tomato, with the mayo? A classic combination that works just as well on a burger.

At White Castle, classically my order was always Two Double Bacon Sliders, and Two Double Jalapeno Cheese Sliders, their Doubles are a tripple decker mini burger in which the mid tier bun does a great job of bringing you some more sopping wet steamy onion juice sponge goodness, and while it seems they've phased out their "Jalapeno Cheese" in recent times, it was a great Pepper Jack type cheese.

At Checkers/Rallys, I go for the Big Buford, it is a big one and much like the Whopper it has all of the salad, but they use shredded lettuce which I feel works great on burgers and sweet RED onions instead of the typical white, this is a unique choice and one I thoroughly approve of. It also differs from the Whopper in that they add mustard to the ketchup and mayo combination, almost a statement to say "this burger goes ALL the way", as well as two pieces of cheese one per patty, it's truly a big burger and it does satisfy.

White Castle serves crinkle cut fries which are kind of novel so I'll give them third place, they satisfy a certain cafeteria craving other fries don't. Then, I guess I'll say Wendy's fries are better than BK, they have the charm of featuring some potato skin which is a bit novel whilst not being a totally impressive fry, while BK comes in last place with simply a somewhat sorry fry that becomes kind of bad the less hot it becomes, which by BK standards usually isn't that hot to begin with.

For Chicken, I say McDonalds does it best simply because of their McNuggets, which are the only crisp/crunchy fast food nugget, the rest are more crumby/crumbly. Followed by Wendy's, then Checkers, then White Castle, than BK.

com:
When I was growing up, my mom would always use an electric beater to make mashed potatoes, and I never cared for them because the texture always felt a little gluey. When I moved out, I started using a hand masher. It did a great job, but sometimes if I was in a hurry or wasn't very thorough, there could be lumps in it.

A couple of months ago I picked up a ricer, and holy shit. It changes the game. I still use a hand-masher for when I leave the skins on, but if I want a really fluffy mash or if I'm making a topping for a cottage pie, the ricer is such an incredible tool. It comes out super fluffy and all you need to use to stir in your butter, milk, and seasoning is a spoon. I've also heard you can use them to make cauliflower or carrot mash, as well as use a large setting to make spatzle.

Also, parboiled baby (new) potatoes that are lightly smashed until the skins pop (but the filling doesn't come oozing out), that are then baked or fried are amazing. Love the crispy exterior and the creamy insides with some flaked salt.

Pumpkin soup

>butterscotch pumpkin
>cut into large pieces, remove seeds and skin
>preheat slowcooker on high
>lightly oil
>throw pumpkin in, allow to cook on high for 4 hours or so
>be careful because you can still burn the pumpkin if left unattended
>once completely soft and slightly browned on the bottom, get blender out and make into a puree
>put back in slow cooker

at this point you can either add your seasonings or add some more ingredients like diced ham or onions that have been browned in a pan, leave on high for another hour and serve

uhh not really something worth memorizing or all that special, like I don't recall the specific ratios and you'll probably need to alter lots of things based on how big your *pot* is

but basically you cook some corn meal, yeast and sugar and water for a while, put it in some glass bottles let it sit for a week or two, then you cook the fermented mash at the right temperature to distill it (which these crock pot/rice cooker things are OK for this stage; for the absolute bottom of the barrel budget tier); which requires the only other vaugely specialized piece of equipment for the entire process... some copper tubing, cut the bottom off a plastic bottle, and hot glue, for your distillation tower. and then distill multiple times

refer to image. it's more of a 'process' than a recipe. I guess if you're in some shtf situation and need to distil alcohol or are some like serious alcoholic in a sharia law nation and need your fix it's fine. but please note; it's very jank, and will require a few runs to even get to work (imprecise temperature controls) with your setup

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15561779
The key point just dumping it all together misses is coating all the flour dusts with butter.
If you don't coat the flour with butter, it will tend to clump.

And, of course, you are stuck with a white bechamel instead of a pale golden blonde bechamel, because milk has water, so the flour can't toast because liquid water keeps the temperature below toasting.

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15561779
No, it doesn't matter in terms of result.

The flavour gets more complex as you toast the flour in the butter, and that can also give you deeper colours, but that's all.

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15561779
No. The point is to coat each particle of flour with fat before introducing the milk, which makes it less liable to create clumps where the exterior of a bit of flour gets hydrated but the interior stays dry. Look up "beurre manie."

name: Anonymous
com:
>>15560366
This exactly. Just because you can live to 60 on a diet, doesn't mean it's something we should all choose.

We know where the populations with the highest longevity and lowest age-related diseases ate. It was more than just the turn of the century Okinawan diet, there have been meta-studies that include millions of participating individuals. The traits they share are these: the diet is typically very high in vegetables and fruits, gets 45-55% of their calories from carbohydrates such as tubers, grains, and beans, ate meat and poultry and fish sparingly, and avoided highly processed foods and added sugars. So when you have the choice between potatoes and a potato chip, choose potatoes. Between rice and wheat or breads and pastas made from their flours, you lean toward the whole grains. Sugar from fruit is fine (they've literally tested 10-15 servings of fruit per day on top of a traditionally healthy diet with no excess weight gain or change in biomarkers), it's added sugar from HCFS and the like that's the deal breaker. Get your healthy fats from stuff like avocado, nuts, and seeds, and just about anything you'd supplement (like fish oil, a multivitamin, etc.) you should be trying to get from whole foods instead.
